n": "selenoprotein", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.687464714050293, "span": {"begin": 758, "end": 771}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:57925"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Glutathione", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9992152452468872, "span": {"begin": 839, "end": 850}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2876"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Glutathione Peroxidase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9850964546203613, "span": {"begin": 839, "end": 861}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2876"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "GPx", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9917538166046143, "span": {"begin": 863, "end": 866}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:35924"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hydroperoxides", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999693751335144, "span": {"begin": 906, "end": 920}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:25824"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Thioredoxin Reductase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.998319149017334, "span": {"begin": 931, "end": 952}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7296"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "TrxR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9985921382904053, "span": {"begin": 954, "end": 958}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7295"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "reduced thioredoxin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.642448902130127, "span": {"begin": 1000, "end": 1019}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:140606"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "SelH, K, S, R, W, and P selenoproteins", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9969280958175659, "span": {"begin": 1062, "end": 1100}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013438"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "thiol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997437596321106, "span": {"begin": 1181, "end": 1186}}, {"id": ["mesh:C442270"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "selenol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997431039810181, "span": {"begin": 1187, "end": 1194}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:55829"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "selenoproteins", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9461560249328613, "span": {"begin": 1209, "end": 1223}}, {"id": ["mesh:D010100"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "oxygen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9996308088302612, "span": {"begin": 1420, "end": 1426}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013438"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "thiol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999329686164856, "span": {"begin": 1495, "end": 1500}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:57925"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "glutathione", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9961327314376831, "span": {"begin": 1510, "end": 1521}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:23511"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cysteinyl", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9996428489685059, "span": {"begin": 1610, "end": 1619}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:32758"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "selenocysteinyl residues", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.8643333911895752, "span": {"begin": 1624, "end": 1648}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:22487"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "aminoacyl", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9991375207901001, "span": {"begin": 1670, "end": 1679}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000596"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "amino acids", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9992407560348511, "span": {"begin": 1854, "end": 1865}}], "text": "Thiol (SH) and selenol (SeH) compounds exhibit reactivity toward electrophiles and oxidants and have high binding affinities for metals (Higdon, 2012; Nagy, 2013; Winterbourn, 2008; Winther, 2014). Glutathione is a thiol-containing tripeptide acting as a cofactor for the enzyme peroxidase and thus serving as an indirect antioxidant donating the electrons necessary for its decomposition of H2O2, and is also involved in many other cellular functions (Kohen, 2002). Selenoproteins contain selenocysteine amino acid residues. The selenoprotein family is composed of proteins exerting diverse functions, among them several are oxidoreductases classified as antioxidant enzymes (Labunskyy, 2014; Reeves, 2009). Relevant for this KER there are two well-studied selenoprotein families which are described to be expressed in the brain; (i) the Glutathione Peroxidase (GPx) family, involved in detoxification of hydroperoxides; (ii) the Thioredoxin Reductase (TrxR) family, involved in the regeneration of reduced thioredoxin (Pillai, 2014), but also the less studied SelH, K, S, R, W, and P selenoproteins (Pisoschi, 2015; Reeves, 2009).    As summarized in the table 1, binding to the thiol/selenol groups of the selenoproteins cited above can result in structural modifications of these proteins, which in turn inhibits their catalytic activity and thereby reduces or blocks their metabolic capacity to neutralize reactive oxygen species (Fernandes, 1996; Rajanna, 1995). Similarly, binding to the thiol group of glutathione will decrease its anti-oxidant capacity.     &nbsp;  Figure (Poole, 2015) Structures of cysteinyl and selenocysteinyl residues within proteins. The aminoacyl groups are shown to the left, with dotted lines representing peptide bonds to the next residue on either side. Both protonated (left) and deprotonated (right) forms of these amino acids are depicted with average pKa values.   &nbsp;  &nbsp;    &nbsp;  &nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:30:07 +0000 2026"}